WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.660
So I am going to switch gears just a little bit and talk about Waldenstrom's, which, as

00:00:04.660 --> 00:00:06.200
you all know, is totally different.

00:00:07.340 --> 00:00:09.320
It is a stepchild.

00:00:09.480 --> 00:00:10.400
We heard about the stepsister.

00:00:10.400 --> 00:00:14.720
This is a stepchild of either lymphoma or myeloma, depending on what hospital you work

00:00:14.720 --> 00:00:14.920
at.

00:00:15.960 --> 00:00:23.920
And we are still in this phase with Waldenstrom's where we use one therapy, like a monotherapy

00:00:23.920 --> 00:00:27.420
of a VTK inhibitor, generally for a lot of our patients.

00:00:28.300 --> 00:00:35.880
You can see here that we use bendamustine rituximab in some cases, but not often, as

00:00:35.880 --> 00:00:37.580
we heard earlier with follicular lymphoma.

00:00:37.580 --> 00:00:43.680
We are trying to move away from using chemotherapy, although if you need a rapid response, then

00:00:43.680 --> 00:00:46.080
in those cases, we might still use bendamustine.

00:00:47.440 --> 00:00:53.740
And we do use mid-88 CXCR4 to help us decide on therapies, and I'll show you a little bit

00:00:53.740 --> 00:00:55.540
of data on that in a second.

00:00:56.260 --> 00:00:58.260
And we do recommend checking TP50.

00:00:58.300 --> 00:01:01.000
We recommend checking TP50 for 17P3 status or for 17P deletion.

00:01:01.500 --> 00:01:05.420
Even though we're not using that yet to choose therapies, I think it's going to be a standard

00:01:05.420 --> 00:01:06.020
in the future.

00:01:06.840 --> 00:01:11.580
So I would say in most cases, we use anibrutinib as a monotherapy currently, bendamustine

00:01:11.580 --> 00:01:13.740
rituximab if we need a rapid response.

00:01:15.500 --> 00:01:20.680
So the reason we recommend checking CXCR4 status in patients with Waldenstrom's, about

00:01:20.680 --> 00:01:23.120
a third of patients have a CXCR4 mutation.

00:01:23.780 --> 00:01:27.480
There are more than 40 different mutations, either nonsense or frame shift.

00:01:28.300 --> 00:01:33.540
There are less major responses, slower responses, and the progression-free survival is more

00:01:33.540 --> 00:01:36.640
limited when patients have a CXCR4 mutation.

00:01:37.160 --> 00:01:42.500
I included here just some data from the Aspen trial you can see at the bottom, which shows

00:01:42.500 --> 00:01:47.340
that the depth of response is less when patients have a CXCR4 mutation.

00:01:48.080 --> 00:01:50.080
The progression-free survival is less.

00:01:50.820 --> 00:01:56.760
You can improve that a little bit by using zanubrutinib rather than ibrutinib in these

00:01:56.760 --> 00:01:57.200
patients.

00:01:58.300 --> 00:02:04.120
In relapse disease, we again recommend that you check MID-88, CXCR4, and TP53.

00:02:04.340 --> 00:02:10.000
TP53 can be acquired in patients as their disease progresses.

00:02:10.960 --> 00:02:17.040
MID-88 is usually pretty standard throughout, and CXCR4, sometimes the sensitivity of testing

00:02:17.040 --> 00:02:20.380
is lower when patients are initially diagnosed, and we might pick it up later.

00:02:20.560 --> 00:02:25.300
I think not because it's a new mutation, but because our methods of testing are just not

00:02:25.300 --> 00:02:26.100
that great right now.

00:02:28.300 --> 00:02:33.520
So in terms of TP53 alterations, so I do think that we're a little behind a lot of other

00:02:33.520 --> 00:02:40.860
diseases in terms of learning about TP53 alterations, and we just have some newer data that's come

00:02:40.860 --> 00:02:43.380
out in recent years about how that affects outcomes.

00:02:44.140 --> 00:02:49.340
So in newly diagnosed patients, depending on the study and the manner in which TP53

00:02:49.340 --> 00:02:56.240
status is determined, about 5% to 15% of patients will have a TP53 alteration, and there are

00:02:56.240 --> 00:02:58.280
higher rates in relapse.

00:02:58.300 --> 00:03:02.160
In relapse disease, particularly if patients have been exposed to chemo, and you can see

00:03:02.160 --> 00:03:09.080
in the graphs on the top that overall survival and then time to need for treatment is shorter

00:03:09.080 --> 00:03:11.420
in patients who have a TP53 mutation.

00:03:13.380 --> 00:03:19.200
And these are the data, again, from the Aspen study that show us that in treatment-naive

00:03:19.200 --> 00:03:24.340
patients, the rates are about 17%, and they increased about 27% in previously treated

00:03:24.340 --> 00:03:24.940
patients.

00:03:25.200 --> 00:03:27.940
And the same data here from Dr. Treon's study showing...

00:03:28.300 --> 00:03:32.460
The same thing, higher rates in patients that are treatment-exposed, and higher rates of

00:03:33.260 --> 00:03:38.460
TP53 alterations in people with prior alkylating and nucleoside analog therapies.

00:03:40.300 --> 00:03:45.340
And again, the outcomes in patients with the TP53 mutation are worse.

00:03:46.060 --> 00:03:51.340
We can overcome those a little bit with sanubrutinib, but we're still looking for better

00:03:51.340 --> 00:03:56.420
therapies, and we're a little behind the myeloma world in terms of using bispecifics or CAR-T,

00:03:56.420 --> 00:04:01.000
which maybe will make more of a difference for these patients than the BTK inhibitors

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:02.600
that we standardly use now.

00:04:04.340 --> 00:04:10.260
So in terms of optimizing treatments or standard therapy, as you all know, the BTK inhibitors

00:04:10.260 --> 00:04:17.380
or chemoimmunotherapy, the ongoing trials in Waldenstrom's now are trying to compare

00:04:17.380 --> 00:04:18.760
or combine those.

00:04:19.340 --> 00:04:25.760
So the trial that's the farthest along is the ACALA bendamustine rituximab trial, and

00:04:26.420 --> 00:04:34.660
that shows that 64% of patients achieved VGPR, CR, and 10% undetectable MRD in the initial data

00:04:34.660 --> 00:04:40.420
that was presented from this trial. And there's a similar trial using XANU, one in the U.S. and one

00:04:40.420 --> 00:04:47.140
in China. We don't have final results from any of these trials yet. And then some upcoming data that

00:04:47.140 --> 00:04:51.220
we're looking forward to in the near future is moving away completely from chemotherapy and

00:04:51.220 --> 00:04:56.340
treatment-naive patients and using sonorotoclax with XANU. There are 20 cycles that we're looking

00:04:56.340 --> 00:05:00.820
forward to. We don't have data from that trial yet. And then the ongoing recruitment is happening

00:05:00.820 --> 00:05:07.460
for pertubrutinib rituximab venetoclax. It's a two-year disease treatment period, and that trial

00:05:07.460 --> 00:05:15.540
is currently enrolling. For relapse Waldenstrom's, we have the lancas-tuximab trial, that if I

00:05:15.540 --> 00:05:22.180
remember to show up on time, I will present that data later at this meeting, and the pertubrutinib

00:05:22.180 --> 00:05:26.260
venetoclax trial as well. So you'll see that.

00:05:26.260 --> 00:05:33.140
That will come up later in the meeting. And sonorotoclax also, for an indefinite period,

00:05:33.140 --> 00:05:40.340
this shows so far an overall response rate of 76%. But we're awaiting final trial data as well for

00:05:40.340 --> 00:05:45.140
that. Additionally, there are the BTK degraders, which I do think are going to play a big role in

00:05:45.140 --> 00:05:50.260
Waldenstrom's treatment going forward. Overall response rate 85% to 90%, as you can see there

00:05:50.260 --> 00:05:56.180
on the slide, in patients who were previously exposed to covalent BTK inhibitors. So I think those

00:05:56.180 --> 00:05:59.860
are pretty high response rates and will play an important role going forward.

00:06:01.620 --> 00:06:08.100
And then upcoming and ongoing clinical trials that I think most importantly I'll focus on really is,

00:06:08.100 --> 00:06:13.220
you know, we don't have a lot of data with bispecifics or with the CAR-T-cell therapies

00:06:13.220 --> 00:06:19.380
in Waldenstrom's. The first bispecific trial specifically for Waldenstrom's is the apcoritumab

00:06:19.380 --> 00:06:25.140
trial. We have a handful of patients on that trial in our site, and actually patients are doing quite

00:06:25.140 --> 00:06:26.100
well.

00:06:26.180 --> 00:06:31.140
And even those with mid-88 negative disease, we have the upcoming ATTENTIMEG trial that will be

00:06:31.140 --> 00:06:36.740
based out of Mayo Clinic. And then we are working hopefully to have some additional bispecific

00:06:36.740 --> 00:06:44.580
T-cell trials or CAR-T-cell trials in the future for Waldenstrom's. Thank you for your attention.
